WEBVTT

00:05.222 --> 00:05.440
.

00:05.483 --> 00:08.051
[soft xylophone music]

00:08.095 --> 00:10.227
- When I was 18,
I wanted a

00:10.271 --> 00:13.665
tattoo of a panda right here,
on my arm,

00:13.709 --> 00:16.668
but, uh,
my girlfriend at the time

00:16.712 --> 00:18.801
talked me into a heart.

00:18.844 --> 00:20.672
- Stop moving.
- Yeah.

00:20.716 --> 00:23.501
I don't know why I thought
a panda would be so cool.

00:23.545 --> 00:24.589
- Well, this tattoo will guide

00:24.633 --> 00:26.330
the external beam radiation

00:26.374 --> 00:28.680
to within less than
a millimeter of your tumor,

00:28.724 --> 00:30.204
so, also cool.

00:30.247 --> 00:32.336
- Yeah, but three dots?

00:32.380 --> 00:34.077
Three dots is so lame.

00:34.121 --> 00:35.600
Why couldn't you give me,
like, a badass teardrop

00:35.644 --> 00:36.775
or a tiger?

00:36.819 --> 00:39.822
- I get that you're nervous.

00:39.865 --> 00:41.606
- Hmm.

00:41.650 --> 00:43.347
- When will you tell the staff?

00:43.391 --> 00:46.176
- I was kind of hoping
they wouldn't notice.

00:46.220 --> 00:49.179
- Four days in you're gonna
start vomiting constantly.

00:49.223 --> 00:50.528
After two weeks, you'll be fed

00:50.572 --> 00:51.660
through a tube in your stomach.

00:51.703 --> 00:53.183
You won't be able to swallow.

00:53.227 --> 00:54.228
There'll be hair loss.

00:54.271 --> 00:56.578
Weight loss.

00:56.621 --> 00:59.102
What I'm saying is, I think
they're gonna notice.

00:59.146 --> 01:01.452
- They're gonna notice, yeah.

01:01.496 --> 01:03.802
I'll tell them.

01:03.846 --> 01:04.803
Somehow.

01:04.847 --> 01:06.196
- Okay.

01:06.240 --> 01:08.764
Hold. Don't move.

01:10.853 --> 01:12.376
Imagine it's a panda.

01:12.420 --> 01:14.335
- [chuckles]

01:14.378 --> 01:18.252
♪

01:18.295 --> 01:20.732
[sirens wailing]

01:20.776 --> 01:23.735
[peppy drum music]

01:23.779 --> 01:29.741
♪

01:29.785 --> 01:31.743
- So in the middle
of stitching up her arm

01:31.787 --> 01:33.571
she asks for a mai tai.

01:33.615 --> 01:35.138
I was like, "Lady,

01:35.182 --> 01:37.227
does this look like
a tiki bar to you?"

01:37.271 --> 01:39.099
Hey, thanks guys.

01:39.142 --> 01:40.665
I would never have made it
from the Bronx without you.

01:40.709 --> 01:43.320
Next time, drinks
are on me, okay?

01:49.413 --> 01:51.198
Stealing snacks again?

01:51.241 --> 01:53.896
- No name, fair game.

01:53.939 --> 01:55.332
Moonlighting before a double?

01:55.376 --> 01:56.333
- So?

01:56.377 --> 01:57.769
Like you don't.

01:57.813 --> 02:00.598
- Yeah, but I'm not
the department chair.

02:03.688 --> 02:04.689
- Later.

02:04.733 --> 02:07.692
- All right.

02:07.736 --> 02:08.693
- Lauren?

02:08.737 --> 02:09.694
Hey, do you know what kind

02:09.738 --> 02:10.695
of Scotch Floyd drinks?

02:10.739 --> 02:12.436
What?
You guys are buds.

02:12.480 --> 02:14.264
- Yeah, it's just weird
hearing him called Floyd.

02:14.308 --> 02:15.831
- Oh, yeah, right.

02:15.874 --> 02:17.441
It's way more normal to call
somebody by their last name.

02:17.485 --> 02:19.182
So Scotch?

02:19.226 --> 02:21.184
- Uh, if he's paying,
whatever's in the well,

02:21.228 --> 02:23.447
and if someone else is paying,
then top shelf.

02:23.491 --> 02:25.362
Why?
- Uh, it's his birthday.

02:25.406 --> 02:27.625
- Oh, man.
Well, good luck.

02:27.669 --> 02:29.279
- Wait, why good luck?

02:29.323 --> 02:30.628
- Well, it just sucks
to start dating a guy

02:30.672 --> 02:31.629
and then have it
be his birthday.

02:31.673 --> 02:33.370
- Does it?
- Yeah.

02:33.414 --> 02:34.806
If he one of those guys
who loves his birthday.

02:34.850 --> 02:36.460
- I love my birthday.
- Not like he does.

02:36.504 --> 02:37.853
It's impossible.

02:37.896 --> 02:39.202
- So you're thinking
I should get something

02:39.246 --> 02:40.464
better than Scotch?
- Yep.

02:40.508 --> 02:42.727
Good luck.

02:42.771 --> 02:47.645
♪

02:47.689 --> 02:49.778
[elevator dings]
- Ah, thank you.

02:49.821 --> 02:51.693
[metallic squeaking]

02:51.736 --> 02:53.651
[sighs] This is too much.

02:53.695 --> 02:55.784
[squeaking]

02:55.827 --> 02:58.178
I don't even know how to...
[sighs]

02:58.221 --> 03:00.876
[squeaking, thudding]
Oh!

03:03.357 --> 03:05.924
- You got me a FloTech
Cell Sorter for my birthday?

03:05.968 --> 03:07.926
- No.
- Man, you shouldn't have.

03:07.970 --> 03:10.973
- I didn't.
- And yet, here it is.

03:11.016 --> 03:13.280
- I guess HCC decided to
upgrade our old cell sorter.

03:13.323 --> 03:14.846
Which, no surprise,
didn't need upgrading.

03:14.890 --> 03:16.457
- Whoa.

03:16.500 --> 03:18.198
- Maybe your girlfriend
pulled some strings?

03:18.241 --> 03:19.895
- Oh, I don't know; this
machine costs 100,000 bucks.

03:19.938 --> 03:21.288
- Which could have been
better spent

03:21.331 --> 03:23.464
almost anywhere else
in the hospital.

03:23.507 --> 03:25.335
- Yes. Bureaucracy.
- Bureaucracy.

03:25.379 --> 03:26.858
- Here, help me get it to the
OR before someone else nabs it.

03:26.902 --> 03:28.338
- You're keeping it?

03:28.382 --> 03:29.731
- Well, possession's 9/10
of the law.

03:29.774 --> 03:31.428
- It's not, actually.

03:31.472 --> 03:33.256
- Well, then I'm invoking
the "finders, keepers" rule.

03:33.300 --> 03:35.519
Just help me move it.
Come on.

03:35.563 --> 03:37.608
[cart squeaking]

03:37.652 --> 03:38.609
How do you,
do you know how to--

03:38.653 --> 03:39.610
Do you know how to do--

03:39.654 --> 03:41.743
[pager buzzing]

03:41.786 --> 03:43.005
It's broken.
[pager buzzing]

03:43.048 --> 03:44.746
- Yeah, well...
[pager beeps]

03:44.789 --> 03:46.008
Bureaucracy.

03:46.051 --> 03:49.881
♪

03:49.925 --> 03:52.275
- Hup, keep walking.

03:52.319 --> 03:54.495
Keep walking.

03:54.538 --> 03:58.020
- I am still very angry.

03:58.063 --> 03:59.804
Down three
with seven seconds left

03:59.848 --> 04:01.719
and Hardaway's sitting
on a bench?

04:01.763 --> 04:03.373
- And then they don't
call a timeout.

04:03.417 --> 04:05.419
- He's our only
three-point shooter.

04:05.462 --> 04:08.030
- Well, to love the Knicks
is to suffer.

04:13.818 --> 04:17.735
- Would you like to watch
the game tonight...

04:17.779 --> 04:19.737
together?

04:19.781 --> 04:20.912
- I can't.

04:20.956 --> 04:22.566
[stirring music]

04:22.610 --> 04:24.264
- Okay.

04:24.307 --> 04:27.571
- I'm getting my one-year chip.

04:27.615 --> 04:28.877
- Chip?

04:28.920 --> 04:30.835
- For being clean.

04:30.879 --> 04:32.750
- I see.

04:32.794 --> 04:35.623
- It's at the downtown Y.

04:35.666 --> 04:37.015
You could come if you'd like.

04:37.059 --> 04:39.714
That would be...
- Strange to get a reward.

04:39.757 --> 04:41.933
- I mean, it's kind of
a big deal.

04:41.977 --> 04:43.761
- I would think that

04:43.805 --> 04:46.590
the real reward would be

04:46.634 --> 04:49.767
not being an addict.

04:49.811 --> 04:51.595
- Okay.

04:51.639 --> 04:54.859
So I guess you're not coming.
- I have a better idea.

04:54.903 --> 04:57.645
Um...

04:57.688 --> 04:59.299
Knicks game? Next week?

04:59.342 --> 05:01.649
♪

05:01.692 --> 05:03.694
- Yeah.

05:03.738 --> 05:06.001
[pager buzzing]

05:07.698 --> 05:09.918
- Patient.

05:09.961 --> 05:12.442
So I'll--I'll see you
next week?

05:12.486 --> 05:16.968
♪

05:18.753 --> 05:20.798
[peppy drum music]

05:20.842 --> 05:22.539
- Uh, Max.

05:22.583 --> 05:23.845
Can I just get your thoughts
on a patient?

05:23.888 --> 05:25.063
- Yeah.
- Um, locally advanced

05:25.107 --> 05:26.064
pancreatic cancer.

05:26.108 --> 05:27.501
- Amenable to surgery?

05:27.544 --> 05:28.763
- Yes, he's prepped
and ready to go.

05:28.806 --> 05:29.807
- Great, then go for the cure.

05:29.851 --> 05:30.808
- There's a catch.

05:30.852 --> 05:31.853
Cardiology work-up

05:31.896 --> 05:32.984
found a left-ventricular

05:33.028 --> 05:34.899
ejection fraction of 35%.

05:34.943 --> 05:36.118
- That is a catch.

05:36.161 --> 05:37.685
- 90% chance he'll die
on the table.

05:37.728 --> 05:39.121
- But a 10% chance he won't.

05:39.164 --> 05:40.818
- Technically. But those
are terrible odds.

05:40.862 --> 05:42.516
- That's for him to decide.

05:42.559 --> 05:44.387
- I can't suggest he go through
with the surgery, can I?

05:44.431 --> 05:45.649
- Why not?

05:45.693 --> 05:47.477
- Because that's like
me saying to you,

05:47.521 --> 05:48.957
"Hey, let's scrap chemo
and wing it

05:49.000 --> 05:50.567
with precision-targeted
therapy."

05:50.611 --> 05:53.657
- Well, some of those trials
show a lot of promise.

05:53.701 --> 05:56.007
- Some show it makes
the disease worse.

05:56.051 --> 05:57.487
[elevator dings]

05:57.531 --> 05:58.749
But we're not talking
about you.

05:58.793 --> 06:00.490
- Right, but

06:00.534 --> 06:02.013
we have to give your patient

06:02.057 --> 06:04.973
both options, right?

06:05.016 --> 06:07.410
- "We"?

06:07.454 --> 06:10.848
♪

06:10.892 --> 06:12.154
- A man named Daniel

06:12.197 --> 06:14.504
was captured by Roman soldiers.

06:14.548 --> 06:16.419
The general told Daniel
he could make--

06:16.463 --> 06:17.768
- Nurse, can you
give us a minute?

06:17.812 --> 06:19.379
- Thank you, he's all yours.

06:19.422 --> 06:20.771
- [laughs] The story was just
getting good.

06:20.815 --> 06:22.033
- Rabbi Skillman, I'd like
to introduce you

06:22.077 --> 06:24.079
to our medical director,
Max Goodwin.

06:24.122 --> 06:25.907
- Goodwin. Is that Jewish?

06:25.950 --> 06:28.649
- Uh, I believe my
great-great-grandmother was,

06:28.692 --> 06:31.086
but I was raised...nothing.

06:31.129 --> 06:32.435
- Then you're Jewish.

06:32.479 --> 06:34.176
- [chuckles] I'll take it.

06:34.219 --> 06:35.699
- So, Dr. Sharpe.

06:35.743 --> 06:37.135
Do you have good news
for me this morning?

06:37.179 --> 06:39.399
Lot of whispering going on.

06:39.442 --> 06:40.878
- I wish I did.

06:42.924 --> 06:44.708
- Okay.

06:44.752 --> 06:45.796
- It's what you feared?

06:45.840 --> 06:46.884
His heart...

06:46.928 --> 06:48.146
- Work-up shows that it's not

06:48.190 --> 06:50.453
pumping blood very well.

06:50.497 --> 06:51.628
- Mm.

06:51.672 --> 06:53.935
The cherry on the cancer cake.

06:53.978 --> 06:56.198
- There's a 90% chance

06:56.241 --> 06:57.765
of dying in surgery.

06:57.808 --> 07:01.029
- Or a 10% chance of a cure.

07:02.552 --> 07:04.075
- Not great odds.

07:04.119 --> 07:06.904
- The other option
is no surgery.

07:06.948 --> 07:09.080
You can go home.

07:09.124 --> 07:10.560
Spend a year
of good-quality life

07:10.604 --> 07:11.909
with the people you love.

07:11.953 --> 07:14.085
We'll make sure
that you're comfortable.

07:14.129 --> 07:16.914
[stirring music]

07:16.958 --> 07:19.221
- Like any good conundrum,

07:19.264 --> 07:21.223
I believe I'll need some time
to think about this.

07:21.266 --> 07:22.790
- Yeah, of course.

07:22.833 --> 07:24.182
And if you have any questions,
I'm here.

07:24.226 --> 07:26.968
- Take all the time you need.

07:27.011 --> 07:28.491
We just want to make sure

07:28.535 --> 07:31.494
you really consider
both options.

07:31.538 --> 07:37.239
♪

07:37.282 --> 07:38.762
- Okay.

07:38.806 --> 07:40.198
Hmm.

07:40.242 --> 07:42.723
Amy.

07:42.766 --> 07:44.812
I see your...

07:44.855 --> 07:47.989
migraines haven't improved.

07:48.032 --> 07:51.035
And, uh...

07:51.079 --> 07:53.081
your triptans did not help.

07:53.124 --> 07:54.517
- No.

07:54.561 --> 07:56.954
- We can run a second MRI,

07:56.998 --> 07:58.608
but I'm afraid we've exhausted

07:58.652 --> 07:59.957
all the traditional treatments.

08:00.001 --> 08:01.524
- Is there anything else...

08:01.568 --> 08:03.221
- Find a better treatment.

08:04.832 --> 08:07.095
- Yes, Mrs. Chiang.

08:07.138 --> 08:09.619
I'm starting to think
that stress

08:09.663 --> 08:11.229
could be a factor.

08:11.273 --> 08:13.797
And we might think
about counseling

08:13.841 --> 08:15.103
as an alternative treatment.

08:18.759 --> 08:20.891
- I speak many languages,
Mrs. Chiang,

08:20.935 --> 08:23.198
but Mandarin is not
one of them.

08:23.241 --> 08:24.721
- Um, my mom is just saying--

08:24.765 --> 08:27.028
- My daughter is here
for migraines.

08:30.945 --> 08:33.643
- I have a colleague,
Dr. Iggy Frome,

08:33.687 --> 08:36.994
and, uh...ah.

08:37.038 --> 08:39.170
He's a wonderful psychiatrist.

08:39.214 --> 08:42.739
[soft, tense music]

08:42.783 --> 08:46.830
♪

08:46.874 --> 08:48.658
Okay.

08:48.702 --> 08:52.183
♪

08:52.227 --> 08:54.055
- "Dr. Ignatius Frome.

08:54.098 --> 08:56.884
Chair of behavioral health."

09:00.975 --> 09:03.194
- Mom. It's just to talk.

09:03.238 --> 09:05.240
One appointment can't hurt.

09:08.896 --> 09:12.073
- Okay, but what if Dr. Frome
could help?

09:12.116 --> 09:15.990
- We don't talk to strangers
about our problems.

09:20.647 --> 09:23.650
[train rushing]

09:25.260 --> 09:28.219
[intense music]

09:28.263 --> 09:30.613
♪

09:30.657 --> 09:32.093
[brakes squealing,
horn honking]

09:32.136 --> 09:35.313
- [screaming]

09:38.969 --> 09:39.404
.

09:39.448 --> 09:41.276
[tense music]

09:41.319 --> 09:43.234
♪

09:43.278 --> 09:44.627
- What do we got?

09:44.671 --> 09:45.715
- "Failure to fly."

09:45.759 --> 09:46.977
Bowery stop, attempted suicide.

09:48.849 --> 09:49.893
- Escort her out of here.

09:49.937 --> 09:50.894
Would you give me the rundown?

09:50.938 --> 09:52.374
- Amy Chiang. 21.

09:52.417 --> 09:53.767
Got lucky, landed
on the track bed

09:53.810 --> 09:55.029
so the train went
right over her.

09:55.072 --> 09:56.683
Left her with lacerations,

09:56.726 --> 09:57.727
possible patellar fracture.

09:57.771 --> 09:59.599
- Amy, look at me.

09:59.642 --> 10:00.687
Can you move your leg?

10:00.730 --> 10:01.905
- Got her chart.

10:01.949 --> 10:03.994
- Get ortho and prep
for surgery. Now.

10:04.038 --> 10:05.343
- You're not gonna
believe this,

10:05.387 --> 10:06.518
but she was here this morning.

10:06.562 --> 10:08.912
- Why?
- Seeing Dr. Kapoor.

10:12.612 --> 10:13.961
- First generation
Chinese-American.

10:14.004 --> 10:15.963
First to go to college
in her family.

10:16.006 --> 10:17.878
Scholarship. Works full-time
at the family restaurant.

10:17.921 --> 10:19.444
Grades started to slip.

10:19.488 --> 10:20.663
She came in complaining
of migraines.

10:20.707 --> 10:21.925
Medication didn't work,

10:21.969 --> 10:23.884
at which point Kapoor
suggested stress

10:23.927 --> 10:25.755
as a possible trigger,
and then referred her to me.

10:25.799 --> 10:28.410
The next thing you know...
- Only 21.

10:28.453 --> 10:30.020
- Possible undiagnosed
severe depression.

10:30.064 --> 10:31.543
- We saw this
at the Chinatown clinic.

10:31.587 --> 10:32.544
Called it
"the F train disease."

10:32.588 --> 10:33.850
- Never heard of it.

10:33.894 --> 10:35.460
- Well, the F train
runs through Chinatown,

10:35.504 --> 10:37.549
and a lot of women would
use it as a last resort.

10:37.593 --> 10:39.769
Uh, depression can be...

10:39.813 --> 10:41.989
hard to accept
in some Asian communities.

10:42.032 --> 10:43.468
- In many communities.

10:43.512 --> 10:44.469
- Yeah, well, stigma or no,

10:44.513 --> 10:45.775
if we don't help Amy,

10:45.819 --> 10:48.343
she will probably try
to kill herself again.

10:48.386 --> 10:50.606
[cart rattling]

10:50.650 --> 10:52.869
- I've never seen anything
so beautiful.

10:54.697 --> 10:56.307
- What does it even do?

10:56.351 --> 10:57.657
- Oh, nothing, you know,

10:57.700 --> 10:59.397
just separates
the white blood cells

10:59.441 --> 11:03.663
from the red blood cells
with the flick of a switch.

11:03.706 --> 11:06.622
Best birthday present ever.

11:06.666 --> 11:10.060
- [giggling] You really
are a birthday dork.

11:10.104 --> 11:12.933
- My mom worked two jobs
seven days a week,

11:12.976 --> 11:14.848
but every year on my birthday
she took the whole day off

11:14.891 --> 11:16.371
and took me to the bookstore,

11:16.414 --> 11:17.720
where she bought me
as many books

11:17.764 --> 11:19.330
as I could carry.

11:19.374 --> 11:22.072
- [laughs] Correction.
You are just a dork.

11:22.116 --> 11:24.509
- No way.

11:26.729 --> 11:28.383
It's the wrong connector.

11:28.426 --> 11:30.951
It's not compatible
with any of the machines.

11:30.994 --> 11:32.561
- Call an electrician.

11:32.604 --> 11:34.563
- No, we'd have to upgrade
the whole OR.

11:34.606 --> 11:37.566
This is just $100,000 worth
of useless junk.

11:43.441 --> 11:45.487
- Quality genes.
I bet he's smart, too.

11:45.530 --> 11:48.011
You don't get abs like that
without crushing the SATs.

11:48.055 --> 11:50.710
- When I want input
on my choice of sperm donor,

11:50.753 --> 11:52.712
I'll let you know.
- Right.

11:52.755 --> 11:54.539
Has the rabbi decided
on the surgery yet?

11:54.583 --> 11:56.541
- I usually give my patients
a little more time,

11:56.585 --> 11:58.761
you know, when it comes
to life-and-death decisions.

11:58.805 --> 11:59.893
- Well, you know,
in poker they say,

11:59.936 --> 12:01.372
"You think long,
you think wrong."

12:01.416 --> 12:02.765
- Well, that's interesting,

12:02.809 --> 12:04.419
because in oncology we say,

12:04.462 --> 12:06.726
"Do the opposite
of poker players." [laughs]

12:06.769 --> 12:08.815
- Well, let's see what
the patient has to say.

12:08.858 --> 12:10.120
- No. Max!

12:10.164 --> 12:11.861
- Hmm?
- I think you're getting

12:11.905 --> 12:13.645
too invested in this.
- Really?

12:13.689 --> 12:15.386
Isn't this the same amount
of "too invested" I always get?

12:15.430 --> 12:16.779
I take it,
if you were the rabbi,

12:16.823 --> 12:18.694
you would take the year.
- I have my reasons.

12:18.738 --> 12:20.478
- Well, I respect
those reasons,

12:20.522 --> 12:22.045
except they're ridiculous
because a year is nothing.

12:22.089 --> 12:23.481
- A year is everything

12:23.525 --> 12:24.961
if it's with someone
that you love.

12:25.005 --> 12:26.746
- There's a year, and then
there's a year with cancer.

12:26.789 --> 12:28.748
Believe me, most people
would take the surgery.

12:28.791 --> 12:30.706
- Max. Signatures.

12:30.750 --> 12:31.968
- Dora, my dear, how are you?

12:32.012 --> 12:33.448
- Ah, good, thanks.

12:33.491 --> 12:34.971
- Actually you're not.
- I'm not?

12:35.015 --> 12:35.972
- You have terminal cancer.

12:36.016 --> 12:37.017
- What?

12:37.060 --> 12:38.061
- Ah, you're settling a debate

12:38.105 --> 12:39.062
between Sharpe and me.

12:39.106 --> 12:40.716
- Oh, do I have to?

12:40.760 --> 12:42.936
- Choice one: get a surgery
that would cure you.

12:42.979 --> 12:44.894
Right?
Or choice two:

12:44.938 --> 12:47.810
go home, do nothing, and die.

12:47.854 --> 12:50.030
- Definitely the surgery.
- No, hang on.

12:50.073 --> 12:51.161
Max is trying to sway the jury.

12:51.205 --> 12:52.597
Here's the real situation.

12:52.641 --> 12:54.599
Option one: have a surgery
so risky

12:54.643 --> 12:56.471
you're more likely to survive
a plane crash,

12:56.514 --> 12:58.473
or go home and have
a good year with your family

12:58.516 --> 13:00.127
living in peace and comfort.

13:00.170 --> 13:02.782
- Definitely the year.
Can I be done now?

13:02.825 --> 13:04.435
- No.
- Yes.

13:04.479 --> 13:05.436
Thank you, Dora.

13:05.480 --> 13:06.568
See?

13:06.611 --> 13:08.613
It's all in the presentation.

13:08.657 --> 13:11.573
- He's doing the surgery.

13:11.616 --> 13:13.967
It's a no-brainer.

13:14.010 --> 13:16.796
- I'm not doing the surgery.

13:16.839 --> 13:19.146
The risk is too great, I...

13:19.189 --> 13:21.452
I was prepared, but now...

13:21.496 --> 13:23.628
90% death rate?

13:23.672 --> 13:25.108
I'm a Jets fan.

13:25.152 --> 13:27.676
Historically, luck has not
been in my favor.

13:27.719 --> 13:28.895
- [crying]

13:28.938 --> 13:30.940
- Hey, hey, hey.

13:30.984 --> 13:34.248
This is the path
God chose for me.

13:34.291 --> 13:35.902
We're gonna have a good year.

13:35.945 --> 13:38.469
- You could take more time...

13:38.513 --> 13:40.820
to decide, if you want.
You can...

13:40.863 --> 13:43.257
go home and talk it over
with the rest of your family,

13:43.300 --> 13:44.824
your congregation...

13:44.867 --> 13:47.522
- I-I'm--I'm at peace
with my decision.

13:47.565 --> 13:50.046
I accept my circumstances
for the way they are,

13:50.090 --> 13:51.961
not the way I want them to be.

13:52.005 --> 13:53.833
- We both do.

13:53.876 --> 13:55.878
- I want the year.

13:55.922 --> 13:57.880
- And New Amsterdam will be
here to support you

13:57.924 --> 13:59.534
every step of the way.

13:59.577 --> 14:01.841
- Thank you, Dr. Sharpe.

14:01.884 --> 14:03.625
- Now let's talk about
what comes next.

14:03.668 --> 14:04.974
- Mm.

14:05.018 --> 14:07.629
- We're going to connect
you with staff members

14:07.672 --> 14:11.241
who will discuss home care
and medication.

14:11.285 --> 14:13.940
Rebecca's going to be
incredibly important.

14:13.983 --> 14:17.857
And the focus of this year
is you.

14:17.900 --> 14:19.554
Your comfort.

14:19.597 --> 14:23.166
[somber music]

14:23.210 --> 14:25.647
- Mrs. Chiang.
- How is she?

14:25.690 --> 14:29.694
- Amy is stable.
- When can I take her home?

14:29.738 --> 14:31.740
- Hi, um, I'm Dr. Frome.

14:31.783 --> 14:33.873
Dr. Kapoor gave you
my card earlier.

14:35.918 --> 14:38.007
I just wanted to say
I'm very, very sorry

14:38.051 --> 14:40.053
about what happened today.

14:40.096 --> 14:41.184
When your daughter
gets out of surgery,

14:41.228 --> 14:42.664
we would like to discuss

14:42.707 --> 14:44.231
inpatient psychiatric care
with you.

14:44.274 --> 14:47.147
- She's not crazy.
She's a good girl.

14:47.190 --> 14:49.105
- No, no, we know that.
We know she is.

14:49.149 --> 14:51.891
She just needs help.

14:51.934 --> 14:53.544
- We're going to go now.

14:53.588 --> 14:54.937
- Okay. We want what's best
for your daughter,

14:54.981 --> 14:56.286
and I'm sure you do too.

14:56.330 --> 14:58.071
But, uh, you're not
the patient here.

14:58.114 --> 14:59.246
Amy is.

14:59.289 --> 15:01.552
Mrs. Chiang,

15:01.596 --> 15:04.077
your daughter jumped
in front of a subway train.

15:04.120 --> 15:07.123
- She didn't jump.

15:07.167 --> 15:08.603
- I beg your pardon?

15:08.646 --> 15:11.040
- She didn't jump.
She slipped.

15:11.084 --> 15:18.047
♪

15:18.091 --> 15:20.136
[child crying]

15:20.180 --> 15:22.051
[chair squeaking]

15:22.095 --> 15:27.143
[child crying]

15:27.187 --> 15:28.928
[chair slams, crying continues]

15:28.971 --> 15:30.277
- Come here, baby.
Come here.

15:30.320 --> 15:32.192
♪

15:32.235 --> 15:34.803
- Studies found
that docs working shifts

15:34.846 --> 15:36.109
of 30 hours or more

15:36.152 --> 15:39.112
end up making
36% more mistakes.

15:39.155 --> 15:42.028
- I'm fine.
I'm a polyphasic sleeper.

15:42.071 --> 15:43.768
- That's not a real thing.

15:43.812 --> 15:47.381
- Me and Thomas Edison.
We thrive off of short naps.

15:47.424 --> 15:50.210
- Define "thrive."

15:50.253 --> 15:53.648
You gave the subway jumper
20 milligrams of morphine?

15:53.691 --> 15:54.866
Is she dead?

15:54.910 --> 15:58.348
- No. Two. 2 milligrams.

15:58.392 --> 15:59.871
It's a typo.

15:59.915 --> 16:01.308
I didn't submit it.

16:01.351 --> 16:04.746
I was gonna proof it.

16:04.789 --> 16:06.313
- 36%.
- Shut up.

16:06.356 --> 16:07.705
- Okay.

16:09.055 --> 16:11.231
[crying continues]

16:11.274 --> 16:13.015
[indistinct voice on PA]

16:13.059 --> 16:16.018
[intensifying
electronic music]

16:16.062 --> 16:23.112
♪

16:34.689 --> 16:34.863
.

16:34.906 --> 16:37.257
- Hey, Doc.
- Hey.

16:37.300 --> 16:38.736
Thought I was gonna miss you.

16:38.780 --> 16:40.782
- Everything all right?

16:40.825 --> 16:43.437
- Yeah, um...

16:43.480 --> 16:44.742
Uh...

16:44.786 --> 16:47.658
[quietly] I--I need to ask you
a question.

16:47.702 --> 16:49.486
And, uh...

16:49.530 --> 16:51.923
this isn't me,
Dr. Goodwin, asking.

16:51.967 --> 16:54.491
This is, uh...

16:56.798 --> 16:58.713
This is me, Max.

16:58.756 --> 17:01.107
- What is it, Max?

17:01.150 --> 17:04.632
- That decision you made...

17:04.675 --> 17:07.461
I don't think
I could have made it.

17:07.504 --> 17:10.855
And you seem so at peace,
I mean...

17:10.899 --> 17:14.207
real, in your bones, at peace.

17:14.250 --> 17:15.904
- You want to know
how I can be at peace

17:15.947 --> 17:17.210
when I know I'm going to die?

17:17.253 --> 17:18.298
- Yeah.

17:20.865 --> 17:24.130
- Do you know the story
of Abraham and Isaac?

17:24.173 --> 17:25.131
- No.

17:25.174 --> 17:27.698
- Okay, so...

17:27.742 --> 17:30.310
Abraham and Sarah
have no children.

17:30.353 --> 17:32.138
But when they're very old,

17:32.181 --> 17:34.662
God gives them a son, Isaac.

17:34.705 --> 17:36.533
And then God asks Abraham

17:36.577 --> 17:38.796
to sacrifice Isaac.
Kill him.

17:38.840 --> 17:41.147
And he'll reward him
with as many children

17:41.190 --> 17:44.541
as there are stars in the sky
and sand in the sea.

17:44.585 --> 17:48.632
And Abraham, being a good
and faithful man,

17:48.676 --> 17:51.418
takes Isaac up the mountain
to sacrifice him.

17:51.461 --> 17:54.812
And God rewards him for it.

17:54.856 --> 17:55.987
That's choice one.

17:56.031 --> 17:58.251
- [chuckles shortly]

17:58.294 --> 18:00.949
- But what if Abraham said no?

18:00.992 --> 18:02.429
What if Abraham said,

18:02.472 --> 18:03.734
"There's lots of stars
in the sky,

18:03.778 --> 18:05.475
"but only one Isaac,

18:05.519 --> 18:07.999
"who I waited 100 years for,

18:08.043 --> 18:10.785
"and I'd rather spend the time
I have left on this Earth

18:10.828 --> 18:14.528
with him and Sarah,
reward be damned"?

18:14.571 --> 18:17.313
That's choice two.

18:17.357 --> 18:20.621
Two impossible choices.

18:20.664 --> 18:23.754
So I took the one
that makes me happier.

18:23.798 --> 18:26.540
- I have a confession.

18:26.583 --> 18:27.889
- Wrong religion,
but I'm listening.

18:27.932 --> 18:29.630
- I have cancer.
[clears throat]

18:29.673 --> 18:32.285
[stirring music]

18:32.328 --> 18:35.375
- I'm sorry.

18:35.418 --> 18:39.466
- Chemo stars tomorrow,
and, uh...

18:39.509 --> 18:44.558
what I'm learning is that
I'm not a good patient.

18:44.601 --> 18:48.866
[chuckles]
'Cause I'm...scared.

18:48.910 --> 18:52.392
And I'm frustrated.

18:52.435 --> 18:54.916
And I'm angry, you know?

18:54.959 --> 18:58.615
♪

18:58.659 --> 19:01.618
I don't--I don't know
what to do. [breath hitches]

19:02.924 --> 19:06.797
- Cancer changes everything
and nothing at all.

19:06.841 --> 19:10.018
♪

19:10.061 --> 19:11.541
- [breathes deeply]

19:12.673 --> 19:15.893
- [distorted] Where is
my sandwich?

19:15.937 --> 19:19.810
[overlapping voices
and coughing]

19:19.854 --> 19:22.944
I need a sandwich!

19:22.987 --> 19:25.381
I need a sandwich.

19:25.425 --> 19:26.774
- Would you mind
checking it out?

19:26.817 --> 19:29.429
- Yeah, no problem.
[indistinct voice on PA]

19:29.472 --> 19:32.432
[spacey music]

19:32.475 --> 19:39.526
♪

19:43.660 --> 19:45.401
- How are you feeling, Rodger?

19:45.445 --> 19:47.708
- His asthma seems better.

19:47.751 --> 19:48.970
[distorted] Do you know
how much longer

19:49.013 --> 19:52.408
we have to stay?

19:52.452 --> 19:53.453
- I'm sorry, what?

19:53.496 --> 19:55.629
- When can we go?

19:55.672 --> 19:57.935
- Yeah, uh, since your husband

19:57.979 --> 19:59.720
uh, also has hypertension,

19:59.763 --> 20:02.766
we're going to need to watch
his pressure overnight.

20:02.810 --> 20:04.986
I'm afraid the recital's gonna
have to wait.

20:05.029 --> 20:07.380
- Is he gonna be okay?

20:07.423 --> 20:09.033
- Absolutely.

20:09.077 --> 20:12.602
♪

20:12.646 --> 20:14.474
- Okay, you were right.

20:14.517 --> 20:16.650
Polyphasic sleepers are real.

20:16.693 --> 20:18.478
- Yeah, uh, you were right too.

20:18.521 --> 20:21.002
Um, I'm gonna hit
the on-call room

20:21.045 --> 20:24.353
and just crash for five.

20:29.358 --> 20:31.708
[thud]
What the?

20:31.752 --> 20:33.841
Can someone get whatever
the hell this is

20:33.884 --> 20:35.451
out of my ED?

20:35.495 --> 20:36.887
- You better be ready
to party.

20:36.931 --> 20:38.411
- What?

20:38.454 --> 20:39.760
- Uh, I thought about
what you said

20:39.803 --> 20:41.544
and I decided to throw Floyd
a surprise party

20:41.588 --> 20:42.850
right after work.
- Right.

20:42.893 --> 20:44.678
Great idea. He'll love it.

20:47.550 --> 20:48.856
- Just a few more
quick questions.

20:48.899 --> 20:50.074
Cake or pie?

20:50.118 --> 20:52.773
- Neither. Uh, cobbler.
Peach.

20:52.816 --> 20:55.732
- Does he like karaoke?

20:55.776 --> 20:58.344
- Only if he can do
power ballads.

20:58.387 --> 21:00.607
- Can't wait to see that.

21:00.650 --> 21:03.044
- You can't, really?

21:03.087 --> 21:04.611
- Are balloons too much?

21:04.654 --> 21:06.047
- Nothing is too much.

21:06.090 --> 21:08.745
- Thanks, you rock.

21:16.753 --> 21:20.496
[knocking]

21:20.540 --> 21:22.019
Dr. Bloom?

21:22.063 --> 21:23.412
I could really use your opinion

21:23.456 --> 21:25.414
on the patient in Bay 3.

21:29.940 --> 21:33.074
Did you have a good nap?

21:37.731 --> 21:38.862
- Hi there, Amy.

21:38.906 --> 21:40.037
I am, uh, I'm Dr. Frome,

21:40.081 --> 21:41.387
I believe Dr. Kapoor

21:41.430 --> 21:42.388
spoke to you about me earlier?

21:42.431 --> 21:43.824
- Um...

21:43.867 --> 21:45.652
- Do you mind if I sit?

21:49.569 --> 21:51.614
Thank you.

21:51.658 --> 21:53.660
Okay, so.

21:53.703 --> 21:55.183
[clears throat]

21:55.226 --> 21:59.230
I would like to talk to you
about what happened today.

22:00.971 --> 22:04.540
You are very lucky
to be alive.

22:04.584 --> 22:06.455
You know that, right?

22:12.113 --> 22:15.856
Okay, tell me if any of these
feel true for you.

22:15.899 --> 22:18.467
Can't concentrate at school.

22:18.511 --> 22:21.731
Chronic fatigue,
but you can't sleep.

22:21.775 --> 22:23.994
You feel like a failure

22:24.038 --> 22:27.041
despite your
many accomplishments.

22:27.084 --> 22:28.956
Feel hopeless.

22:30.218 --> 22:32.612
- I thought it was stress.

22:32.655 --> 22:35.658
- That's depression.

22:35.702 --> 22:38.879
And millions of people
suffer from it.

22:38.922 --> 22:40.620
- I have a lot of good things
in my life.

22:40.663 --> 22:42.709
I shouldn't have depression.

22:42.752 --> 22:43.884
- Yeah.

22:43.927 --> 22:47.627
Depression doesn't work
that way.

22:47.670 --> 22:50.499
But the good news

22:50.543 --> 22:52.022
is it's highly treatable.

22:52.066 --> 22:55.852
[soft music]

22:55.896 --> 22:57.506
- How?

22:57.550 --> 23:00.204
- Well, the first step
is to ask for help.

23:03.207 --> 23:06.080
I like to start
with talk therapy.

23:06.123 --> 23:09.039
- What if my mom found out?

23:09.083 --> 23:12.739
Or my dad?

23:12.782 --> 23:15.655
They'd think I was acting weak.

23:15.698 --> 23:17.221
- I think it's a good thing

23:17.265 --> 23:20.224
to talk to others
about our problems.

23:22.531 --> 23:25.665
- I'm on my parents' insurance.

23:25.708 --> 23:27.101
- Okay.

23:27.144 --> 23:30.321
- They would know
I was going to therapy.

23:30.365 --> 23:32.672
They'd think I was
talking about them

23:32.715 --> 23:34.761
or telling family secrets.

23:34.804 --> 23:39.200
♪

23:39.243 --> 23:42.333
They'd stop talking to me.

23:42.377 --> 23:45.206
- Amy...
- I can't.

23:45.249 --> 23:46.773
I'm sorry.

23:49.340 --> 23:50.690
- Okay.

23:55.912 --> 23:57.653
Amy shouldn't have to suffer

23:57.697 --> 23:59.089
because her community is afraid
of mental illness.

23:59.133 --> 24:01.048
- It is not about fear.
It's about shame.

24:01.091 --> 24:03.659
- No, it's about stigma.
- You have to understand

24:03.703 --> 24:05.095
that they are afraid
of what others think.

24:05.139 --> 24:06.793
- Yeah, well, who cares
what others think?

24:06.836 --> 24:08.359
- Look, we all want
what's best for her, okay?

24:08.403 --> 24:10.187
But we can't fight every
cultural stigma in one day.

24:10.231 --> 24:12.363
- Told you it was stigma.
- It's shame.

24:12.407 --> 24:14.104
- We've got a patient that
we want to help,

24:14.148 --> 24:15.845
but we can't help her
because of all these

24:15.889 --> 24:19.283
stupid insurance forms.

24:19.327 --> 24:21.721
- You're right.
- See?

24:21.764 --> 24:22.983
About what?

24:23.026 --> 24:24.637
- Downcode it.
- Are you serious?

24:24.680 --> 24:25.812
- I had to do it for girls
whose parents

24:25.855 --> 24:26.987
wouldn't allow them
birth control.

24:27.030 --> 24:29.076
Billed it as
"round ligament pain."

24:29.119 --> 24:30.077
- Huh.

24:30.120 --> 24:31.339
- We would look incompetent.

24:31.382 --> 24:33.297
- But you'll help the patient.

24:33.341 --> 24:35.561
- You want us to defraud
the hospital?

24:35.604 --> 24:37.650
- Exactly.

24:37.693 --> 24:40.087
- Okay...

24:40.130 --> 24:42.176
[peppy drum music]

24:42.219 --> 24:43.917
♪

24:43.960 --> 24:45.222
- Max.

24:45.266 --> 24:47.137
What the hell did you tell
the rabbi?

24:47.181 --> 24:48.878
- I have no idea
what you're talking about.

24:48.922 --> 24:51.925
- After you talked to him,
he changed his mind.

24:51.968 --> 24:53.753
You have just talked him
into a risky surgery

24:53.796 --> 24:56.146
that will most likely
lead to his death.

25:06.069 --> 25:06.461
.

25:06.505 --> 25:08.463
- Sorry, Jane?
Give us a second.

25:08.507 --> 25:10.857
Please?

25:10.900 --> 25:12.815
- You're wondering why
I changed my mind.

25:12.859 --> 25:15.470
- I am praying it is not
because of me.

25:15.514 --> 25:17.951
- What can I say?
You made a good case.

25:17.994 --> 25:20.519
- This is a high-risk surgery.

25:20.562 --> 25:22.695
And for me to tip the scales
in any way

25:22.738 --> 25:23.826
with my own baggage

25:23.870 --> 25:26.220
is the definition of unethical.

25:26.263 --> 25:27.526
- Tough luck.

25:27.569 --> 25:29.528
You did.

25:29.571 --> 25:31.094
Max.
- Rabbi.

25:31.138 --> 25:33.575
- Max, I make my own decisions.

25:33.619 --> 25:36.665
Yeah, I could be home
with family.

25:36.709 --> 25:39.233
But I'd still be a patient.

25:39.276 --> 25:41.975
That's not the life I want.

25:42.018 --> 25:43.585
- But--
- If I do this,

25:43.629 --> 25:46.196
tomorrow I'll be better
or I'll be dead,

25:46.240 --> 25:48.634
but I won't be a patient.

25:50.897 --> 25:53.595
- Not sure that clears me
of the malpractice suit, but...

25:53.639 --> 25:56.772
- [chuckles] Max, go.
I absolve you.

25:56.816 --> 25:57.860
- Wrong religion.

25:57.904 --> 25:59.209
- Oh, now you're being picky.

25:59.253 --> 26:01.516
- [chuckles]

26:05.999 --> 26:07.653
Sorry. Rabbi?

26:09.655 --> 26:13.223
Did Abraham actually sacrifice
his own son?

26:15.008 --> 26:17.053
- No.

26:17.097 --> 26:19.882
An angel came down
and stopped him.

26:19.926 --> 26:22.493
But he was going to.

26:22.537 --> 26:25.975
And it was enough
to pass God's test.

26:26.019 --> 26:29.109
And God rewarded him
with as many children

26:29.152 --> 26:32.547
as there are stars in the sky
and sands in the sea:

26:32.591 --> 26:35.506
the Jewish people.

26:35.550 --> 26:37.944
Some things are worth the risk.

26:37.987 --> 26:40.947
[hopeful music]

26:40.990 --> 26:46.648
♪

26:46.692 --> 26:49.912
- Why is there a cell sorter
in the hallway?

26:49.956 --> 26:51.697
- It won't connect
to the other machines.

26:51.740 --> 26:53.002
Bureaucracy.

26:53.046 --> 26:54.830
- Tell HCC

26:54.874 --> 26:55.831
to take it back.

26:55.875 --> 26:57.093
- They won't.

26:57.137 --> 26:58.312
It's like we're working
for the army.

26:58.355 --> 26:59.313
- Well, it can't live here.

26:59.356 --> 27:00.314
- I know. Can you take it?

27:00.357 --> 27:01.707
- And do what with it?

27:01.750 --> 27:04.100
- I don't know.
But it's my birthday.

27:06.712 --> 27:07.843
- Dr. Goodwin, Sandra Fall
from billing.

27:07.887 --> 27:09.018
- Yes. You left me a message?

27:09.062 --> 27:10.716
- Yeah, and you didn't
call me back.

27:10.759 --> 27:12.108
- I knew there was something
I forgot to do today.

27:12.152 --> 27:13.327
- Um, are you aware that

27:13.370 --> 27:14.328
two of your doctors
are downcoding?

27:14.371 --> 27:16.069
- Downcoding?

27:16.112 --> 27:17.853
- Yeah, it's when doctors bill
for something small

27:17.897 --> 27:19.333
but provide
more expensive care.

27:19.376 --> 27:20.595
- Why would they do that?

27:20.639 --> 27:21.857
Because if they were upcoding,

27:21.901 --> 27:23.337
they could make money,
but downcoding--

27:23.380 --> 27:24.860
- Yeah, exactly.
So they told me

27:24.904 --> 27:27.080
to put down CPT code 90868

27:27.123 --> 27:28.821
for transcranial
electrical stimulation

27:28.864 --> 27:30.257
for patient Amy Chiang,

27:30.300 --> 27:31.867
but that doesn't require
three weekly sessions

27:31.911 --> 27:33.826
in the psych ward,
so I will also notify--

27:33.869 --> 27:35.349
- Okay, you got me.
I told them to do it.

27:35.392 --> 27:38.047
I just hoped they would do it
a little better.

27:38.091 --> 27:39.745
- Uh, wait, you told
your doctors

27:39.788 --> 27:41.268
to extort money
from the hospital?

27:41.311 --> 27:42.791
- Well, it sounds really bad
when you say it like that,

27:42.835 --> 27:44.227
but, uh,

27:44.271 --> 27:45.707
we were just trying
to help a patient.

27:45.751 --> 27:46.926
- Yeah, and it's my job
to make sure

27:46.969 --> 27:48.057
the hospital has enough money

27:48.101 --> 27:49.276
to help all our patients.

27:49.319 --> 27:50.712
[thud]
- When is somebody

27:50.756 --> 27:52.322
gonna get this thing
out of here?

27:52.366 --> 27:54.020
- You bring up
an excellent point.

27:54.063 --> 27:57.937
- So how do you intend
to make up the lost revenue?

27:57.980 --> 28:01.027
- Would $100,000 cover it?

28:01.070 --> 28:02.811
- You can do that?

28:02.855 --> 28:05.161
Call therapy something else?

28:05.205 --> 28:07.120
- We want to get you
the help that you need

28:07.163 --> 28:08.730
any way we can,

28:08.774 --> 28:10.253
so we're gonna
start therapy in here,

28:10.297 --> 28:12.081
while you're in recovery,
three times a week.

28:12.125 --> 28:14.693
And, uh, and I will navigate
your school schedule

28:14.736 --> 28:16.738
and your work schedule.

28:16.782 --> 28:19.610
Your mother will never
find out.

28:19.654 --> 28:21.830
- But it's a lie.

28:21.874 --> 28:23.745
- On paper, yes.

28:23.789 --> 28:25.747
- [chuckles wryly]

28:25.791 --> 28:27.793
And what will I tell
my mother

28:27.836 --> 28:30.143
when she asks
about the brain stimulation?

28:30.186 --> 28:33.189
- Well, you can tell her
it was very stimulating.

28:34.974 --> 28:37.716
- So then I will be lying
to my mother.

28:37.759 --> 28:39.761
And to my father.
- It's...

28:39.805 --> 28:41.632
it's for your mental health.
- She'll know.

28:41.676 --> 28:44.940
And even if she doesn't
say anything...

28:44.984 --> 28:46.289
she'll judge me.

28:47.943 --> 28:49.292
- I can teach you some
coping mechanisms.

28:49.336 --> 28:53.035
- She won't...love me the same.

28:56.082 --> 28:59.215
Is there a coping mechanism
for that?

29:01.914 --> 29:04.003
- The downcoding will work.

29:04.046 --> 29:07.136
But it's not gonna help,
not in the long run.

29:07.180 --> 29:09.008
The stress of having to lie
to her family

29:09.051 --> 29:11.140
is only going to exacerbate
her depression--

29:11.184 --> 29:12.838
her sense of isolation.

29:12.881 --> 29:15.144
- Our only option is
to work around the mother.

29:15.188 --> 29:16.450
- I think that's the problem.

29:16.493 --> 29:17.973
I don't think we should
work around her.

29:18.017 --> 29:19.235
I think we should bring her in.

29:19.279 --> 29:20.454
- For therapy?
- Yeah.

29:20.497 --> 29:22.108
They need to do it together.

29:22.151 --> 29:23.805
- The whole reason
we are here is because

29:23.849 --> 29:26.112
the mother is against
talking to anyone.

29:26.155 --> 29:28.854
- I know, but we have
to get her on board,

29:28.897 --> 29:31.378
or we're gonna lose Amy.

29:33.162 --> 29:35.817
- Okay.
- Okay.

29:35.861 --> 29:39.255
[tense music]

29:39.299 --> 29:41.780
[door opening]

29:41.823 --> 29:43.433
- Rodger Conway's
gone into A-fib.

29:43.477 --> 29:44.870
- What?

29:44.913 --> 29:46.872
- Sorry, I can get
someone else.

29:46.915 --> 29:48.395
- No, just, just give me a sec.

29:48.438 --> 29:51.485
- No, we can handle it.

29:51.528 --> 29:54.880
- I'm fine. I'm fine.

29:54.923 --> 29:57.143
[alarms beeping]

29:57.186 --> 30:00.886
- SVT. Ventricular rate of 160.

30:00.929 --> 30:02.278
Dr. Bloom?
- Uh, how's the patient?

30:02.322 --> 30:03.845
Any chest pain?

30:03.889 --> 30:05.760
- I would ask him,
but he's unresponsive.

30:05.804 --> 30:07.980
- Okay. Uh, carotid massage.

30:08.023 --> 30:09.895
- He's a set-up
for carotid stenosis.

30:09.938 --> 30:12.375
He'll stroke out.
We need a heavy hitter.

30:12.419 --> 30:14.943
- Okay. Okay.

30:14.987 --> 30:17.337
[alarms beeping rapidly]

30:17.380 --> 30:20.383
- What do you want us
to do, Dr. Bloom?

30:20.427 --> 30:23.430
[beeping continues]

30:27.651 --> 30:27.826
.

30:27.869 --> 30:29.958
- Dr. Bloom, we need
your instructions.

30:30.002 --> 30:31.307
- Yes.
- Yes?

30:31.351 --> 30:32.831
- BP's down to 95/50.

30:32.874 --> 30:35.137
- Dr. Bloom.

30:35.181 --> 30:36.878
- Okay. Okay.

30:36.922 --> 30:39.185
[alarms beeping]

30:39.228 --> 30:43.015
Okay.

30:43.058 --> 30:45.756
Atenolol, 5 milligram, IV.

30:45.800 --> 30:46.757
- You mean adenosine.

30:46.801 --> 30:48.803
- No, I said atenolol.

30:48.847 --> 30:51.110
Atenolol.

30:51.153 --> 30:53.155
- All right.
- Got it. Here.

30:57.159 --> 30:59.727
- BP's down to 90/50.

30:59.770 --> 31:01.033
- Mr. Conway?

31:01.076 --> 31:03.731
Are you with us?

31:03.774 --> 31:06.299
Still unresponsive.

31:06.342 --> 31:09.215
- The medication will take
a minute to work.

31:09.258 --> 31:10.694
- BP's down to 86.

31:10.738 --> 31:11.870
- He's about to convert
to VTACH.

31:11.913 --> 31:12.958
- Blood pressure's
still dropping.

31:13.001 --> 31:14.220
- We usually shock this rhythm.

31:14.263 --> 31:15.786
- Don't. No.
This med will work.

31:15.830 --> 31:17.353
- We need to shock him now.

31:17.397 --> 31:19.573
- No, j--just wait.

31:19.616 --> 31:22.619
[alarms beeping]

31:22.663 --> 31:25.622
[intensifying music]

31:25.666 --> 31:28.234
♪

31:28.277 --> 31:30.627
Just stop!

31:34.370 --> 31:36.372
[beeping slows]

31:36.416 --> 31:37.808
- He's back.

31:40.159 --> 31:43.031
- Normal sinus rhythm.
The medication worked.

31:45.816 --> 31:47.601
- What just happened?

31:47.644 --> 31:50.082
- You're okay, Mr. Conway.

31:50.125 --> 31:52.258
It's okay.
You're okay.

31:52.301 --> 31:55.348
[machines beeping steadily]

31:59.874 --> 32:01.006
- Okay, one last
quick question,

32:01.049 --> 32:02.137
and it's kind of funny.

32:02.181 --> 32:03.791
How old is Floyd going to be?

32:03.834 --> 32:05.358
- I don't know.
He's not my boyfriend.

32:05.401 --> 32:08.970
We just slept together
a couple of times.

32:09.014 --> 32:11.016
- [sighs]

32:15.150 --> 32:22.114
♪

32:25.030 --> 32:28.424
- There must be a part
of you that knows...

32:28.468 --> 32:32.167
that your daughter
did not slip...

32:32.211 --> 32:36.084
that she tried to end
her life today.

32:36.128 --> 32:39.305
I know it's hard to accept.

32:39.348 --> 32:42.830
When a child needs help,
one may think,

32:42.873 --> 32:45.180
"I did a bad job as a parent."

32:46.921 --> 32:49.054
One may wonder,

32:49.097 --> 32:51.708
"Why I didn't see
the signs sooner?"

32:53.754 --> 32:57.845
Our children aren't perfect.

32:57.888 --> 33:01.022
And why should they be?

33:01.066 --> 33:02.284
We are not.

33:13.208 --> 33:15.297
- He's a good man.

33:16.995 --> 33:19.736
Does that count for something?

33:19.780 --> 33:22.913
- In here, no.
But...

33:22.957 --> 33:26.743
everywhere else, yes.

33:26.787 --> 33:28.136
- [sighs]

33:28.180 --> 33:31.357
He was always going to do
the surgery, I think.

33:31.400 --> 33:35.796
He just needed to explore
the alternatives

33:35.839 --> 33:38.494
to know it wasn't for him.

33:41.889 --> 33:45.197
- Do you...

33:45.240 --> 33:48.069
resent him for it?

33:48.113 --> 33:50.289
- I love him for it.

33:50.332 --> 33:52.334
[soft music]

33:52.378 --> 33:56.904
♪

33:56.947 --> 33:59.211
- Hi.

33:59.254 --> 34:01.082
Just came by to check on you.

34:01.126 --> 34:02.823
How you feeling?

34:02.866 --> 34:06.218
- Hmm, like I've been hit
by an F train.

34:06.261 --> 34:09.264
- Whoa.
Solid.

34:09.308 --> 34:13.051
Solid jokes
are a very good sign.

34:13.094 --> 34:15.401
- I'm sorry I can't go
behind my mother's back.

34:17.577 --> 34:19.970
- You know... [clears throat]

34:20.014 --> 34:24.975
You are obviously
a very, very loyal,

34:25.019 --> 34:26.542
very caring daughter.

34:26.586 --> 34:28.196
I see that.

34:28.240 --> 34:31.417
And you're part of a very
tight-knit, close family,

34:31.460 --> 34:33.071
and you care what they think.

34:36.335 --> 34:38.815
- I know it sounds...

34:38.859 --> 34:40.904
silly...

34:40.948 --> 34:43.559
but...

34:43.603 --> 34:48.564
the hardest part
of every day is...

34:48.608 --> 34:50.436
just getting out of bed.

34:50.479 --> 34:53.439
♪

34:53.482 --> 34:56.964
I lay there thinking about

34:57.007 --> 35:00.141
all the things
I have to get done.

35:00.185 --> 35:03.797
I imagine it all in my mind.

35:03.840 --> 35:06.104
And one by one,

35:06.147 --> 35:09.324
I fail at everything.

35:12.632 --> 35:16.026
I don't finish my schoolwork.

35:16.070 --> 35:19.465
I'm late for work.

35:19.508 --> 35:23.295
I say the wrong thing
at home, and...

35:23.338 --> 35:27.603
then I think maybe
I shouldn't even try.

35:27.647 --> 35:30.345
So I lay there for a while...

35:33.000 --> 35:35.916
All the time, wishing

35:35.959 --> 35:38.484
that I could
just tell my mom...

35:38.527 --> 35:41.226
[voice breaking]
How much pressure I feel

35:41.269 --> 35:43.576
to make her proud.

35:46.144 --> 35:47.667
- Ma!

35:51.453 --> 35:53.238
- I told your mother
how we will

35:53.281 --> 35:56.197
bill your insurance.
- [sobs]

35:56.241 --> 35:59.461
- She said it was quite clever.

35:59.505 --> 36:03.073
- I--yeah, I would like to--
if it's okay with you--

36:03.117 --> 36:06.555
